  "text": "Synaptic consolidation depends on plasticity-related proteins, since consolidation can be prevented by application of plasticity-related proteins synthesis inhibitor [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . For example, a strong tetanus in one pathway applied 1 h before a weak tetanus leads to consolidation. But this consolidation fails if the application of the inhibitor starts before the first induction, and lasts until 1 h after the second induction (see Fig. 1d ). However, if the inhibitor is applied only after the first induction (see Fig. 1e ), both pathways are consolidated (see [CITATION_3] Figure 2 for more details). Thus, the plasticity-related proteins synthesized from the first induction are also available to the second pathway. Finally, synaptic consolidation depends on dopamine D1/D5 receptors (Sajikumar and Frey 2004a; [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] ).",
